Blocks.Text: spelt <th>. The final <e> keeps breathe, loathe, seethe, sheathe, soothe,
teethe, wreathe, bathe, lathe, swathe, clothe visually distinct from breath,
loath (also spelt loth), seeth (/'si:jr0/, archaic third person singular present
tense form of see), sheath, sooth, teeth, wreath, bath, lath, swath, cloth. For
the few minimal pairs differing only in having /0/ or /d/ see section 9.36.
The fact that both /0/ and /d/ are spelt <th> is useful in writing: people
whose accents have different distributions of the two phonemes nevertheless
spell the relevant words identically. This is particularly the case with some
plural nouns, e.g. baths pronounced /ba:dz/ in RP but /bæðs/ by many
people from the North of England; the singular has /0/ in both cases. But
this does not help people trying to read unfamiliar words containing <th>
